                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d843">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77/1812: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Crane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-11-09T16:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 9, 1920—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 9—10:18 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>364. Your 122, May 22, 3 p.m. Consideration [for] American business urgently
                    requires at least working settlement of American municipal rights and
                    obligations Harbin. In view of recognized Chinese altered status <hi
                        rend="italic">vis à vis</hi> new railway agreement and position of Russians,
                    I venture to suggest that American consul Harbin be empowered in consultation
                    with Chinese to draft between the two Governments agreement for the approval of
                    Department. Harbin Taoyin recently in Peking intimated his willingness for early
                    settlement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Crane</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
